,Recommended,298600,32939655,Posted: 28 June,all,chromosome_thief123,
76561197983662248,Recommended,298600,11633344,"Posted: 10 August, 2014",all,TechieRefugee,"To start: I used to add a header to these reviews, but since it sometimes made the review too long to submit, I've opted to leave it on my Backloggery page.Gameplay: Lovely Planet is a game that can most easily be described as, ""You got Super Meat Boy in my FPS!"" The level design largely reflects on Super Meat Boy's level design ethos in that levels are pretty short, typically lasting around 15-20 seconds, but are packed with plenty of obstacles to make things challenging. These obstacles range from friendlies that you can't shoot or else you'll end the level, apple launchers in which you have to shoot the apples before they hit the ground, baddies that can shoot homing shots which you have to shoot out of the air (don't worry, it's a lot easier than it sounds), as well as plenty of other obstacles. Worlds one through three are quite a bit of fun; in fact, there was really only one level that I didn't like out of these first 62 levels.Then comes World 4. I'm just gonna be blunt; World 4 is stage memorization central. Why? First and foremost on the bad design checklist is thick fog. Seriously, designers, limiting the player's vision is not a good way to create challenge; it's just a quick path to frustrating the player. There's also plenty of points in this world where you pretty much have to take shots in the dark to be able to complete the level (See Level 4-20 which the designers had to be high to think was a good idea). Whenever you consider that a condition for completion of the game is 100% accuracy on all stages, this really becomes one hell of a frustrating experience. Second on the bad idea checklist for world 4 are shots that literally come out of nowhere. No, that's not just the fog fooling you; these shots literally come out of thin air (obscured by the fog, of course), and you can't see them when you look forward at the stage before attempting it. The only saving grace for the average player is that these stages are among the shortest in the game, but for the completionists, this can be the worst world, as some of the par times areridiculouslystrict. Worlds one through three took me 30 minutes, 50 minutes, and 60 minutes to complete respectively. World four took over three hours and even then I didn't 100% the world.  As for world five... world four has put me off too heavily for me to want to play the game anymore right now. Maybe in a couple of months.Maybe world five will be the big comeback from world four. I sure hope so. Again, worlds one through three were excellent, save for that one stage. It's just too bad about world four. 7/10.Story: Not really any here, so I'm not gonna bother going into detail about it.Graphics: The game sure does look great; at least, until world four where everything becomes terrible and fog. Man, though; world four really is an absolute blight on this game in nearly every respect (even in music, but I'll get to that later). But anyways, at least for the worlds that are actually good, the game really does look great. It's certainly a game that'll look great ten, maybe even twenty years down the line. You can't say that for a lot of games. As for the technical aspects, the game says that it runs at a solid 60FPS, and I can verify that it does indeed run at a solid 60FPS. No lag spots whatsoever. Also, thanks to the simplistic nature of the graphics, you can run this on pretty modest hardware. So yeah, the graphics side of the game was definitely not a disappointment. 5/5.Sound: Only the OST to talk about here, and - *sigh* - yes, the world four song is the weakest of the bunch. Apart from that, the OST is excellent. Calum Bowen sure did a great job with this one. The tracks are sort of like if you mixed Ape Escape's OST with any Katamari OST. Very catchy, very quirky, and just very good. As for the sound design, it uses Engine of Whimsy +10. Good stuff. 5/5.Overall scores are: 7/0/5/5; 8.5/10. Man, if it weren't for world four, gameplay would get a 9/10. Everything just went so far downhill in that world. Oh well; I'll be editing this review later on when I play world five, so maybe it'll give it a shot in the arm to bring it up to 8 or something. As for now, my advice is to play worlds one through three and then stop."
