,Recommended,298600,11764443,"Posted: 18 August, 2014",all,Serenade,"Alright, so I would give this game an 8/10 at most, but there are still a lot of things wrong with it.Let's start off with what the game is.Lovely planet is basically an first-person shooter where you are trying to get to the end of the level as fast as you can while shooting all the enemies, and avoiding any other obstacles. The game starts off easy, and dying is quite forgiving. Every level has a maximum yield of three stars; One for beating the level, another for beating it within a time limit, and one for having 100% accuracy.As the game progresses, you will most likely find yourself redoing levels over and over and over because you missed a shot, or you weren't quick enough causing you to not get all three stars. There are basic mechanics in the beginning, and as the game progresses, there are much more complex ones. It really tries to teach you how to play the game during the whole game without too much obvious tips.Now for the bad of the game.Sadly, the game doesn't feel as if it is made with all the effort the developer could have put into it. The first thing you will find is that the game doesnt have settings to change mouse sensitivity, or even a way to rebind keys. There is also no cross hair for your gun, which can be frustrating considering you are striving for that 100% accuracy. There isn't much else to do after the game is done, making this game pretty straightforward to complete.If you are looking for a game to just try and complete without any worry of how many lives you have, or if you just want to try and challenge yourself by completing every level, this is a good game for you. It has a ton of secrets in it, and the achievements work just fine. If you don't like games that can be frustrating, or games that have no storyline whatsoever, then I would recommend looking for another game. This game has a casual feel to it, but it feels a lot like a bullet hell type of casual fps."
