76561198067164698,Recommended,298600,13856171,"Posted: 5 January, 2015",all,Zargasheth,"The combination of first-person shooter and precision platformer is tricky to pull off, but with the exception of one major design flaw, Lovely Planet does it pretty well.The first aspect of this game that stuck out to me was the minimal, pastel-color visual design. Combined with the aggressively cheery (and quite good) J-pop soundtrack, it helps mitigate that the game is (at points) ridiculously difficult--I know I would probably have lost my patience with a game of this style that insisted on being grim and gritty. But, beyond that, this kind of game just flows better with minimal environments. By stripping away most potential distractions, the path and objectives (shoot all the red things, don't shoot the blue things, get to the lavender thing) become very clear.This is important, because Lovely Planet is a game that encourages you to move very quickly: if you stop moving, you will probably die. This can lead to a pretty rocky start, but as you get the hang of the game, you get better and better at whizzing through levels, bouncing around with your impossible levels of FPS air control and felling enemies with single shots. As such, the game's biggest strength is that its level design facilitates this kind of gameplay. The levels are quite hard, but they are constructed so that finding the right path through them is fun rather than a grind.One criticism I have seen leveled at the game is that the gameplay can get somewhat monotonous, but I think this is more due to the visual design than the individual levels. The environments don't change very much between worlds, which, although preserving the nicely minimal atmosphere, gets dull. Also, some of the later enemies' abilities aren't very well explained, and given that everything instantly kills, it can be kind of hard to tell what an enemy is doing the first few times it gets you. However, this doesn't weigh too much on the game compared to the one big problem:A lot of the challenge comes from tests of accurate shooting, rather than tricky platforming jumps or constant reflex tests. This is quite a sensible approach, but it would be significantly more fun if the gun had a crosshair. As it is, it doesn't, and given that the second and third worlds are largely based around skeet-shooting of a sort (enemies that kill you if they hit the ground) and enemies with homing projectiles that you have to shoot out of the air, respectively, this adds an unnecessarily irritating learning curve to aiming.Still, none of this overrules the fact that the first time I started to write this review, I thought, ""Wait, why am I writing about Lovely Planet when I could be playing Lovely Planet?"" and stopped. Once you get the hang of aiming and jumping, it's got addictive gameplay and a nice difficulty curve, set against a pleasant and cheery background. If you're strange like me and find ultrahard trial-and-error gameplay relaxing in a way, this comes recommended; otherwise, proceed with caution."
