,Recommended,298600,24443154,"Posted: 21 July, 2016",all,Yellow Lime,"The music is great, hands down the best part of the game. Kudos to the music guy Calum Bowen.The game itself... isn't all that great.The graphics need some more baking, even for a budget Katamari Damacy / Nobi Nobi tribute.There are some lazy-looking particle effects and there are great differences in the level of graphic detail during gameplay (the tiny purple stars and Japanese phrases vs. the huge featureless terrain), which gives the game a heterogeneous look (in a bad way).There are hours of content, but the level design is haphazard and at times unintuitive. I would have rather had a shorter game with levels that had more care put into them.Also, for those looking for a competitive game, I hope hacked leaderboards don't stop you from enjoying a game (at the time of writing, this game has them). Being about shooting while moving, it's also sorely missing a crosshair, which should have at least been included as an option.If you choose to play it, here's two pieces of advice:1. Turn the SFX off. The SFX consist of lazy, tacky sounds that don't do the music any justice. You lose the tell for the apples being tossed, but it's still worth the awesome (uninterrupted) music.2. If you find the shooting enemies annoying, know that you can kill them by hitting any of their bullets (bug or feature?).Overall, I still think it's a decent game, just not for $6. I'd say grab it on sale if you know what you're getting into, and even then only bother if you like the OST."
