,Recommended,298600,28170810,"Posted: 3 December, 2016",all,Captain W0W,"Lovely Planet is the wierdest mix of a game you will ever play. What happens when you get Super Meat Boy, DOOM, CS GO, Metal Gear Solid and Katamari Damacy in a blender? This happens.The storyrevoles around you shooting up a Japanese town for no disearnable reason, while presumably taking enough LSD to make Jim Morrison blush.It's thought provoking and hits so many relatable points.It may not look like it, but the game is as tough as nails, and has a pretty steep learning curve. It's one of those games that makes you run through a level and demands the best performance from you, taunting you with your time and accuracy after each stage. There's no crosshair either, and one hit from incoming bullets (or anything that is the colour red) instantly kills you, and puts you right back at the start of the level (akin to Super Meat Boy). There are tons of levels to trawl through, with pretty much all of them looking the same, feeling the same and making you do the same things over again. Yet in the hour and a half I've played (at time of writing), it doesn't feel stale at all.Level design is actually really good, with some of the levels being fairly linear and others being open ended enough to give you multiple ways of attempting them, and allows you to experiment with the game's physics and timing. The game rewards ""high-level"" gameplay (and even demands it at some points), which is where the comparason of MGS and Super Meat Boy come from, and there's no feeling like completing a level that had you clay pidgeon shooting apples out of the sky while jumping across a pit shooting 2 projectile firing baddies and getting 100% accuracy and being 2 seconds under par. All while running backwards.A level editor with Steam Workshop support would beperfec. Or at least I haven't discovered it yet.The soundtrack and visual style is why I compared it to Katamari, if you can't tell. Needless to say it's brilliant and gives the game it's confusing theme. You're going to hear the music loop many times, and it doesn't get that irritating, or at least for me it didn't.Performance is brilliant. Constantly smooth 60+ frames from my (non gaming) laptop, with every level loading up fast, which keeps the arcade-y feel for this game at a high. You're going to need every single frame too to keep up with this game.Lovely Planet sucks you in, just when you thought this game would be something you'd purchase on a sale and forget about after playing it for a few hours. I would heavily recommend."
,Recommended,298600,28119863,"Posted: 1 December, 2016",all,Petrichor,"Do not be deceived, Lovely Planet is not for little babby as its aesthetic may imply. Lovely Planet is a true teeth-gritting experience. It may be more apt to call this a puzzle-shooter than anything else, in my opinion. Lovely Planet wants perfection out of you, and it won't settle for anything less than that.The formula per level is simple: shoot all baddies and reach the big pink pole at the end of the map. Simple, right? Well it certainly starts off simple. Soon you'll move up from just shooting stationary baddies to shooting apples out of the air to shooting the baddies' projectiles out of the air to... I'm not too sure what comes after that. Haven't made it past world 3 yet cuz this game is *pretty challenging*.If you're a fan of games like Super Meat Boy, you'll enjoy this. If you prefer games that give you options on how to complete a level, this may not be for you. Overall it's a challenging experience and will really test your FPS skills."
